#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:4
msgid "Warnings Capture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:8
msgid ""
"Starting from version ``3.1``, pytest now automatically catches warnings "
"during test execution and displays them at the end of the session:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:11
msgid ""
"# content of test_show_warnings.py\n"
"import warnings\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def api_v1():\n"
"    warnings.warn(UserWarning(\"api v1, should use functions from v2\"))\n"
"    return 1\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_one():\n"
"    assert api_v1() == 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:25
msgid "Running pytest now produces this output:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:27
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_show_warnings.py\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-6.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"\n"
"test_show_warnings.py .                                              [100%]\n"
"\n"
"============================= warnings summary "
"=============================\n"
"test_show_warnings.py::test_one\n"
"  $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/test_show_warnings.py:5: UserWarning: api v1, should use "
"functions from v2\n"
"    warnings.warn(UserWarning(\"api v1, should use functions from v2\"))\n"
"\n"
"-- Docs: https://docs.pytest.org/en/stable/warnings.html\n"
"======================= 1 passed, 1 warning in 0.12s ======================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:46
msgid ""
"The ``-W`` flag can be passed to control which warnings will be displayed or "
"even turn them into errors:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:49
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q test_show_warnings.py -W error::UserWarning\n"
"F                                                                    [100%]\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"_________________________________ test_one "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_one():\n"
">       assert api_v1() == 1\n"
"\n"
"test_show_warnings.py:10:\n"
"_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _\n"
"\n"
"    def api_v1():\n"
">       warnings.warn(UserWarning(\"api v1, should use functions from "
"v2\"))\n"
"E       UserWarning: api v1, should use functions from v2\n"
"\n"
"test_show_warnings.py:5: UserWarning\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_show_warnings.py::test_one - UserWarning: api v1, should "
"use ...\n"
"1 failed in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:71
msgid ""
"The same option can be set in the ``pytest.ini`` or ``pyproject.toml`` file "
"using the ``filterwarnings`` ini option. For example, the configuration "
"below will ignore all user warnings and specific deprecation warnings "
"matching a regex, but will transform all other warnings into errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:76
msgid ""
"# pytest.ini\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"filterwarnings =\n"
"    error\n"
"    ignore::UserWarning\n"
"    ignore:function ham\\(\\) is deprecated:DeprecationWarning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:85
msgid ""
"# pyproject.toml\n"
"[tool.pytest.ini_options]\n"
"filterwarnings = [\n"
"    \"error\",\n"
"    \"ignore::UserWarning\",\n"
"    # note the use of single quote below to denote \"raw\" strings in TOML\n"
"    'ignore:function ham\\(\\) is deprecated:DeprecationWarning',\n"
"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:97
msgid ""
"When a warning matches more than one option in the list, the action for the "
"last matching option is performed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:100
msgid ""
"Both ``-W`` command-line option and ``filterwarnings`` ini option are based "
"on Python's own `-W option`_ and `warnings.simplefilter`_, so please refer "
"to those sections in the Python documentation for other examples and "
"advanced usage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:107
msgid "``@pytest.mark.filterwarnings``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:111
msgid ""
"You can use the ``@pytest.mark.filterwarnings`` to add warning filters to "
"specific test items, allowing you to have finer control of which warnings "
"should be captured at test, class or even module level:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:115
msgid ""
"import warnings\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def api_v1():\n"
"    warnings.warn(UserWarning(\"api v1, should use functions from v2\"))\n"
"    return 1\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.filterwarnings(\"ignore:api v1\")\n"
"def test_one():\n"
"    assert api_v1() == 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:130
msgid ""
"Filters applied using a mark take precedence over filters passed on the "
"command line or configured by the ``filterwarnings`` ini option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:133
msgid ""
"You may apply a filter to all tests of a class by using the "
"``filterwarnings`` mark as a class decorator or to all tests in a module by "
"setting the :globalvar:`pytestmark` variable:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:136
msgid ""
"# turns all warnings into errors for this module\n"
"pytestmark = pytest.mark.filterwarnings(\"error\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:143
msgid ""
"*Credits go to Florian Schulze for the reference implementation in the* "
"`pytest-warnings`_ *plugin.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:151
msgid "Disabling warnings summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:153
msgid ""
"Although not recommended, you can use the ``--disable-warnings`` command-"
"line option to suppress the warning summary entirely from the test run "
"output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:157
msgid "Disabling warning capture entirely"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:159
msgid ""
"This plugin is enabled by default but can be disabled entirely in your "
"``pytest.ini`` file with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:161
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = -p no:warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:166
msgid ""
"Or passing ``-p no:warnings`` in the command-line. This might be useful if "
"your test suites handles warnings using an external system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:173
msgid "DeprecationWarning and PendingDeprecationWarning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:176
msgid ""
"By default pytest will display ``DeprecationWarning`` and "
"``PendingDeprecationWarning`` warnings from user code and third-party "
"libraries, as recommended by `PEP-0565 <https://www.python.org/dev/peps/"
"pep-0565>`_. This helps users keep their code modern and avoid breakages "
"when deprecated warnings are effectively removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:180
msgid ""
"Sometimes it is useful to hide some specific deprecation warnings that "
"happen in code that you have no control over (such as third-party "
"libraries), in which case you might use the warning filters options (ini or "
"marks) to ignore those warnings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:184
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:186
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"filterwarnings =\n"
"    ignore:.*U.*mode is deprecated:DeprecationWarning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:193
msgid ""
"This will ignore all warnings of type ``DeprecationWarning`` where the start "
"of the message matches the regular expression ``\".*U.*mode is "
"deprecated\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:198
msgid ""
"If warnings are configured at the interpreter level, using the "
"`PYTHONWARNINGS <https://docs.python.org/3/using/cmdline.html#envvar-"
"PYTHONWARNINGS>`_ environment variable or the ``-W`` command-line option, "
"pytest will not configure any filters by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:202
msgid ""
"Also pytest doesn't follow ``PEP-0506`` suggestion of resetting all warning "
"filters because it might break test suites that configure warning filters "
"themselves by calling ``warnings.simplefilter`` (see issue `#2430 <https://"
"github.com/pytest-dev/pytest/issues/2430>`_ for an example of that)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:213
msgid "Ensuring code triggers a deprecation warning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:215
msgid ""
"You can also use :func:`pytest.deprecated_call` for checking that a certain "
"function call triggers a ``DeprecationWarning`` or "
"``PendingDeprecationWarning``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:219
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_myfunction_deprecated():\n"
"    with pytest.deprecated_call():\n"
"        myfunction(17)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:228
msgid ""
"This test will fail if ``myfunction`` does not issue a deprecation warning "
"when called with a ``17`` argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:243
msgid "Asserting warnings with the warns function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:247
msgid ""
"You can check that code raises a particular warning using func:`pytest."
"warns`, which works in a similar manner to :ref:`raises <assertraises>`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:250
msgid ""
"import warnings\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_warning():\n"
"    with pytest.warns(UserWarning):\n"
"        warnings.warn(\"my warning\", UserWarning)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:260
msgid ""
"The test will fail if the warning in question is not raised. The keyword "
"argument ``match`` to assert that the exception matches a text or regex::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:263
msgid ""
">>> with warns(UserWarning, match='must be 0 or None'):\n"
"...     warnings.warn(\"value must be 0 or None\", UserWarning)\n"
"\n"
">>> with warns(UserWarning, match=r'must be \\d+$'):\n"
"...     warnings.warn(\"value must be 42\", UserWarning)\n"
"\n"
">>> with warns(UserWarning, match=r'must be \\d+$'):\n"
"...     warnings.warn(\"this is not here\", UserWarning)\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  ...\n"
"Failed: DID NOT WARN. No warnings of type ...UserWarning... was emitted..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:275
msgid "You can also call func:`pytest.warns` on a function or code string:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:277
msgid ""
"pytest.warns(expected_warning, func, *args, **kwargs)\n"
"pytest.warns(expected_warning, \"func(*args, **kwargs)\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:282
msgid ""
"The function also returns a list of all raised warnings (as ``warnings."
"WarningMessage`` objects), which you can query for additional information:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:286
msgid ""
"with pytest.warns(RuntimeWarning) as record:\n"
"    warnings.warn(\"another warning\", RuntimeWarning)\n"
"\n"
"# check that only one warning was raised\n"
"assert len(record) == 1\n"
"# check that the message matches\n"
"assert record[0].message.args[0] == \"another warning\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:296
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can examine raised warnings in detail using the :ref:"
"`recwarn <recwarn>` fixture (see below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:300
msgid ""
"The :ref:`recwarn <recwarn>` fixture automatically ensures to reset the "
"warnings filter at the end of the test, so no global state is leaked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:308
msgid "Recording warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:310
msgid ""
"You can record raised warnings either using func:`pytest.warns` or with the "
"``recwarn`` fixture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:313
msgid ""
"To record with func:`pytest.warns` without asserting anything about the "
"warnings, pass ``None`` as the expected warning type:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:316
msgid ""
"with pytest.warns(None) as record:\n"
"    warnings.warn(\"user\", UserWarning)\n"
"    warnings.warn(\"runtime\", RuntimeWarning)\n"
"\n"
"assert len(record) == 2\n"
"assert str(record[0].message) == \"user\"\n"
"assert str(record[1].message) == \"runtime\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:326
msgid "The ``recwarn`` fixture will record warnings for the whole function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:328
msgid ""
"import warnings\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_hello(recwarn):\n"
"    warnings.warn(\"hello\", UserWarning)\n"
"    assert len(recwarn) == 1\n"
"    w = recwarn.pop(UserWarning)\n"
"    assert issubclass(w.category, UserWarning)\n"
"    assert str(w.message) == \"hello\"\n"
"    assert w.filename\n"
"    assert w.lineno"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:342
msgid ""
"Both ``recwarn`` and func:`pytest.warns` return the same interface for "
"recorded warnings: a WarningsRecorder instance. To view the recorded "
"warnings, you can iterate over this instance, call ``len`` on it to get the "
"number of recorded warnings, or index into it to get a particular recorded "
"warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:349
msgid "Full API: :class:`~_pytest.recwarn.WarningsRecorder`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:354
msgid "Custom failure messages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:356
msgid ""
"Recording warnings provides an opportunity to produce custom test failure "
"messages for when no warnings are issued or other conditions are met."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:360
msgid ""
"def test():\n"
"    with pytest.warns(Warning) as record:\n"
"        f()\n"
"        if not record:\n"
"            pytest.fail(\"Expected a warning!\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:368
msgid ""
"If no warnings are issued when calling ``f``, then ``not record`` will "
"evaluate to ``True``.  You can then call :func:`pytest.fail` with a custom "
"error message."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:375
msgid "Internal pytest warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:377
msgid ""
"pytest may generate its own warnings in some situations, such as improper "
"usage or deprecated features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:379
msgid ""
"For example, pytest will emit a warning if it encounters a class that "
"matches :confval:`python_classes` but also defines an ``__init__`` "
"constructor, as this prevents the class from being instantiated:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:382
msgid ""
"# content of test_pytest_warnings.py\n"
"class Test:\n"
"    def __init__(self):\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    def test_foo(self):\n"
"        assert 1 == 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:392
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_pytest_warnings.py -q\n"
"\n"
"============================= warnings summary "
"=============================\n"
"test_pytest_warnings.py:1\n"
"  $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/test_pytest_warnings.py:1: PytestCollectionWarning: "
"cannot collect test class 'Test' because it has a __init__ constructor "
"(from: test_pytest_warnings.py)\n"
"    class Test:\n"
"\n"
"-- Docs: https://docs.pytest.org/en/stable/warnings.html\n"
"1 warning in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:404
msgid ""
"These warnings might be filtered using the same builtin mechanisms used to "
"filter other types of warnings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:406
msgid ""
"Please read our :ref:`backwards-compatibility` to learn how we proceed about "
"deprecating and eventually removing features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/warnings.rst:409
msgid ""
"The full list of warnings is listed in :ref:`the reference documentation "
"<warnings ref>`."
msgstr ""
